1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:12,500
Welcome to the BATbern Event Management Platform! Today I'll show you how to plan an event without losing your mind.

2
00:00:12,500 --> 00:00:25,000
We'll go through the complete event lifecycle, from "Oh no, we need an event!" to "Finally over, off to the archive!" In this video, you'll see all the important steps an organizer takes to plan a Berner Architekten Treffen, without panicking.

3
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:31,400
We begin at the Event Dashboard.

4
00:00:31,400 --> 00:00:37,800
This is basically your command center, where you keep track of all events you've ever organized or will organize in the future.

5
00:00:37,800 --> 00:00:44,200
Authentication via AWS Cognito is already done.

6
00:00:44,200 --> 00:00:50,600
You can see your username in the top right, and with that, you have the power to use all functions as an organizer.

7
00:00:50,600 --> 00:00:57,000
With great power comes great responsibility!

8
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:04,000
Now let's create a brand new event! Click the "New Event" button in the top right. Boom! A modal form appears.

9
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:11,000
Don't worry, it looks like a lot, but we'll fill it out together.

10
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:16,666
Event Number. A unique identifier for this event.

11
00:01:16,666 --> 00:01:22,332
The system internally uses the format "BATbern" followed by the number. Basically the birth certificate of your event.

12
00:01:22,332 --> 00:01:28,000
This serves for identification in the database and in URLs.

13
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:33,333
Title. Here comes the name that should excite your participants!

14
00:01:33,333 --> 00:01:38,666
"Boring Architecture Event Number 47" would be honest, but maybe not the best choice.

15
00:01:38,666 --> 00:01:44,000
Choose something meaningful that people will see on the public website.

16
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:48,333
Description. A brief explanation of the event topic.

17
00:01:48,333 --> 00:01:52,666
This information helps interested people understand why they absolutely should register.

18
00:01:52,666 --> 00:01:57,000
Or at least what it's all about.

19
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:06,666
Event Type. Choose between three formats: "Evening" for after-work events, where you can network a bit after work.

20
00:02:06,666 --> 00:02:16,332
"Afternoon" for afternoon sessions, perfect for those who prefer to be on the couch in the evening.

21
00:02:16,332 --> 00:02:26,000
Or "Full Day" for all-day conferences. You'll need lots of coffee for that! This affects scheduling and slot management.

22
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:31,000
Date and Registration Deadline. The event date determines when the event takes place.

23
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:36,000
Please choose a date in the future, we don't support time travel yet.

24
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:41,000
The registration deadline is important for participant management.

25
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:48,000
Venue. Name and address of the venue. So not "in my basement," but a real place with an address.

26
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:55,000
This information will be displayed on the public website so people can actually find their way there.

27
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:02,000
We click "Save" and the event is created. Tada! The system automatically returns to the dashboard, and there it is!

28
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:09,000
Your brand new event in the list. Your baby is born!

29
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:17,000
After event creation, we navigate to the event detail page. Here we can assign tasks to team members.

30
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:25,000
Because why should you do everything alone when you have a whole team? Click "Edit" to open the event form again.

31
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:31,600
Switch to the "Tasks" tab. Here you see a predefined list of standard tasks that come up with every event.

32
00:03:31,600 --> 00:03:38,200
The system knows its stuff, it knows what needs to be done.

33
00:03:38,200 --> 00:03:44,800
For each task, we select a responsible organizer from the dropdown menu.

34
00:03:44,800 --> 00:03:51,400
This ensures that all important activities are clearly assigned and nothing gets forgotten.

35
00:03:51,400 --> 00:03:58,000
Because forgotten tasks lead to chaos, and chaos leads to... well, more chaos.

36
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:07,000
After assigning, we click "Save". The system saves all tasks and returns to the event detail page. Perfect!

37
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:12,600
To review the tasks, we navigate to the task list.

38
00:04:12,600 --> 00:04:18,200
First you see the default filter "My Tasks," which only shows your own tasks.

39
00:04:18,200 --> 00:04:23,800
But we're curious and want to know what the others are up to.

40
00:04:23,800 --> 00:04:29,400
We change the filter to "All Tasks" to see all assignments.

41
00:04:29,400 --> 00:04:35,000
This gives an overview of responsibilities across the entire team. And who might not have anything to do right now.

42
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:45,000
Back on the event detail page, we begin with content planning! The first step is topic selection. Click "Select Topic".

43
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:51,500
A view opens with various topic categories.

44
00:04:51,500 --> 00:04:58,000
The default view shows a list, but we use the Heat Map for a better overview. Because who doesn't love a good heat map?

45
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:03,750
The Heat Map is a two-dimensional matrix that visualizes topics by their popularity and recency.

46
00:05:03,750 --> 00:05:09,500
Light colors show popular topics, basically the rockstars among architecture topics.

47
00:05:09,500 --> 00:05:15,250
Darker colors show less frequently chosen topics. The underdogs who also deserve a chance.

48
00:05:15,250 --> 00:05:21,000
This helps with strategic topic planning based on participant interests.

49
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:27,666
We select a topic from the Heat Map by clicking on a cell. The system marks the selection and displays details.

50
00:05:27,666 --> 00:05:34,332
After confirmation, the system saves the chosen topic and automatically opens the speaker brainstorming view.

51
00:05:34,332 --> 00:05:41,000
The system is like a good assistant, it always knows what comes next!

52
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:46,750
Now we collect potential speakers for the chosen topic!

53
00:05:46,750 --> 00:05:52,500
In this phase, we create a pool of candidates we'll contact later. We add four speaker candidates.

54
00:05:52,500 --> 00:05:58,250
This gives us enough options for outreach, in case not everyone accepts.

55
00:05:58,250 --> 00:06:04,000
Because speakers are like cats - sometimes they just say no for no reason at all.

56
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:08,666
After adding all candidates, we click "Continue to Outreach".

57
00:06:08,666 --> 00:06:13,332
The system automatically switches to the Kanban view, where we can track contact status. Kanban!

58
00:06:13,332 --> 00:06:18,000
That sounds important and organized!

59
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:27,500
We're now in the speaker outreach phase. The Kanban board shows multiple columns that represent the workflow.

60
00:06:27,500 --> 00:06:37,000
From "Who's that?" through "Contacted" to "Hooray, they said yes!" This visualization gives a quick overview of the progress in speaker acquisition.

61
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:41,750
Now we systematically contact all speaker candidates.

62
00:06:41,750 --> 00:06:46,500
For each candidate, we click on the card and open the contact dialog.

63
00:06:46,500 --> 00:06:51,250
This documentation is important for tracking and for other team members who need to check the status.

64
00:06:51,250 --> 00:06:56,000
Otherwise next week someone asks: "Did we contact them already?" And nobody knows. Chaos avoided!

65
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:04,000
After receiving positive responses, we move speakers through the workflow! It's like Tetris, but with people.

66
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:12,000
We use drag-and-drop to move cards between columns. We move four speakers to the "READY" column.

67
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:20,000
In the next step, we move speakers from "READY" to "ACCEPTED". All four READY speakers are moved to ACCEPTED.

68
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:28,000
Smooth as butter!

69
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:31,666
Before speakers can submit their content, we need to publish the topic.

70
00:07:31,666 --> 00:07:35,332
We navigate to the "Publishing" tab and click "Publish Topic".

71
00:07:35,332 --> 00:07:39,000
In the lower area, there's a preview of the event on the public page. Nice, right?

72
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:46,333
Back in the Speakers tab, we now submit presentation content for each speaker. Title, abstract, the usual suspects.

73
00:07:46,333 --> 00:07:53,666
We repeat this process for all three speakers with confirmed presentations. Copy, paste, repeat.

74
00:07:53,666 --> 00:08:01,000
No, just kidding, each speaker has unique content, of course!

75
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:06,500
After content submission comes quality review. Now that we have the content, we can publish the speakers.

76
00:08:06,500 --> 00:08:12,000
We click "Publish Speakers". And here comes the best part!

77
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:17,500
Now on the public website, not only the topic is visible, but also the confirmed speakers with their topics.

78
00:08:17,500 --> 00:08:23,000
The world can see it!

79
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:32,500
Back in the Speakers tab, we now review and approve each submitted presentation. Now we're playing quality control.

80
00:08:32,500 --> 00:08:42,000
Looks good, looks good, that too. We approve all three presentations. Green light for everyone!

81
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:52,000
For slot assignment, we switch to the Sessions view. Click "Manage Slot Assignments". Now we're getting into the timing!

82
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:59,000
For quick initial planning, we use the Auto-Assign function. The system performs automatic assignment. Magic!

83
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:06,000
The system does the work. Manual assignment via drag-and-drop is also possible here.

84
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:13,000
In case you don't trust the computer or just like moving things around.

85
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:17,000
After slot assignment, we click "Back to Event".

86
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:24,666
The final step is agenda publication! The grand finale! Click "Publish Agenda". And...

87
00:09:24,666 --> 00:09:32,332
The event is now fully planned and publicly accessible including detailed agenda! Confetti! Fireworks!

88
00:09:32,332 --> 00:09:40,000
Okay, maybe just in your mind, but still! We made it!

89
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:45,000
After conducting the event, we archive it for history. Switch to the "Overview" tab and click "Edit".

90
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:50,000
Time to retire the event.

91
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:58,000
In the form, select "ARCHIVED" as status. The event was great, but now it's history.

92
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:03,333
For testing purposes, you can override workflow validation.

93
00:10:03,333 --> 00:10:08,666
Enable the checkbox "Override Workflow Validation" and click "Save".

94
00:10:08,666 --> 00:10:14,000
This is basically the emergency exit, in case things don't go according to plan.

95
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:19,250
And that completes the full event workflow! From the first idea to the archive, we've made the whole journey together!

96
00:10:19,250 --> 00:10:24,500
You're now an event management pro! Thank you for your attention!

97
00:10:24,500 --> 00:10:29,750
And remember: planning events is fun, at least with the right software! See you next time.

98
00:10:29,750 --> 00:10:35,000
Greetings from Creator Nissim.

